        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/stefan-kiss/{size}/1359_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-11-08T06:26:05.404Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"johscheuer\" data-post=\"4\" data-topic=\"3639\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://avatars.discourse-cdn.com/v4/letter/j/f475e1/48.png\" class=\"avatar\"> johscheuer:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>For cluster 1 we can make use of the following peer verification rule:</p>\n<p><code>S.CN=fdb-operator,S.OU=cluster1</code></p>\n<p>and for cluster 2:</p>\n<p><code>S.CN=fdb-operator,S.OU=cluster2</code></p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>right, but remember the constraint from the client is that it only uses the first certificate used to connect to a cluster.</p>\n<p>So for cluster2 it will use CN=fdb-operator,OU=cluster1 - which if i\u2019m understanding correctly should fail with a verification of S.CN=fdb-operator,S.OU=cluster2</p>\n<p>we could only have a cluster verification of S.CN=fdb-operator but that means we really have no way of separating clusters\u2026</p>",
